6. ER TO RELATIONAL MAPPING
================================================================================

Mapping rules applied to convert the ER diagram into relational tables:

RULE 1 — Strong Entity → Table
  Each strong entity (Department, Sales_Representative, Lead, Customer,
  Follow_Up, Activity_Log) is mapped to its own relation with its primary key.

RULE 2 — One-to-Many (1:N) → Foreign Key on "Many" Side
  Relationship                  | FK Placement
  ----------------------------|------------------------------------------
  Department → Sales_Rep      | dept_id FK in sales_representatives
  Sales_Rep → Lead            | assigned_to FK in leads
  Lead → Follow_Up            | lead_id FK in follow_ups
  Sales_Rep → Follow_Up       | rep_id FK in follow_ups
  Lead → Activity_Log         | lead_id FK in activity_log
  Sales_Rep → Activity_Log    | rep_id FK in activity_log

RULE 3 — One-to-One (1:1) → FK in One Table with UNIQUE Constraint
  Lead ↔ Customer: lead_id is placed as a FOREIGN KEY in the customers table
  with a UNIQUE constraint, ensuring each lead maps to at most one customer.

RESULTING RELATIONAL SCHEMA:
  departments(dept_id, dept_name, dept_head, location)
  sales_representatives(rep_id, name, email, phone, designation, dept_id)
  leads(lead_id, first_name, last_name, email, phone, source, status,
        assigned_to, created_at, updated_at)
  customers(customer_id, lead_id, company_name, address, conversion_date, total_value)
  follow_ups(followup_id, lead_id, rep_id, followup_date, remarks,
             next_followup_date, status)
  activity_log(log_id, lead_id, rep_id, action, action_date, description)


